# CREDITS — prior art & influences

splock is an independent work, written from scratch and licensed under
Apache-2.0. It nonetheless stands on a body of public ideas, tools, and
research. The list below names every external influence we are aware of,
links to it, and describes — in our own words — what we took from it. Where a
source carries its own license, that license is named so adopters can reason
about their obligations.

We deliberately wrote our documentation and prose from first principles rather
than adapting text from any of these sources, so that splock carries no
attribution or copyleft obligation onto its own readers. The acknowledgements
here are offered out of intellectual honesty, not legal necessity.

---

## Tooling & platform

### Claude Code (Anthropic)
- Reference: Anthropic Claude Code documentation —
  https://docs.anthropic.com/en/docs/claude-code
- splock is a Claude Code plugin. It targets Claude Code's native extension
  surfaces — plugins, slash commands, subagents, skills, and the lifecycle
  hook system (PreToolUse, PostToolUse, SessionStart, Stop, SubagentStop,
  UserPromptSubmit, SessionEnd) — and assumes the Claude Code CLI as its
  runtime host. The hook contract and the plugin manifest format are
  Anthropic's; splock implements against them.

### Spec Kit (GitHub) — MIT License
- Reference: https://github.com/github/spec-kit
- Influence: the idea that an agent should work from an explicit, written
  specification — a structured plan that precedes implementation — rather than
  improvising from a one-line prompt. splock's plan -> implement -> verify
  lifecycle, and its insistence that a plan be a durable, reviewable artifact,
  are in the same spirit. We did not copy Spec Kit's templates, commands, or
  code; our two-call planner, schema set, and orchestrator format are our own.

