## Security research

splock's deterministic enforcement spine — sealed-state hooks, a path-intent
and collision registry, suppression-pattern blocking, and a separately-pinned
verifier model that an executor cannot talk its way past — is a direct response
to the threat model articulated by the following work. We treat an LLM agent as
an untrusted component whose instructions can be hijacked, and we put the
safety-critical decisions in deterministic code outside the model's control.

### OWASP Top 10 for LLM Applications — CC BY-SA 4.0
- Reference: https://owasp.org/www-project-top-10-for-large-language-model-applications/
- License: Creative Commons Attribution-ShareAlike 4.0 International.
- Influence: the catalog of LLM-application risk classes — prompt injection,
  insecure output handling, excessive agency, and overreliance in particular —
  informed which failure modes splock's hooks are designed to make
  structurally impossible rather than merely discouraged in a prompt. No OWASP
  text is reproduced here; this is a named acknowledgement of the threat
  taxonomy, written in our own words, and therefore does not propagate the
  ShareAlike obligation to splock's own documentation.

### Greshake et al. (2023) — indirect prompt injection
- Reference: Kai Greshake, Sahar Abdelnabi, Shailesh Mishra, Christoph Endres,
  Thorsten Holz, Mario Fritz, "Not what you've signed up for: Compromising
  Real-World LLM-Integrated Applications with Indirect Prompt Injection,"
  arXiv:2302.12173 (2023). https://arxiv.org/abs/2302.12173
- Influence: the demonstration that content an agent merely *reads* (files,
  tool output, retrieved text) can carry adversarial instructions is the core
  reason splock never trusts in-band prose to enforce a boundary. Enforcement
  always lives in a hook or a CLI exit code, never in skill or agent prose that
  a hostile payload could overwrite or contradict. This is a citation of the
  research finding, in our own words; no figures or text from the paper are
  reproduced.

